<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910417-0179</DOCNO><DOCID>910417-0179.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>04/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   BUSH SAID the U.S. and its allies would establish refugeecamps in northern Iraq.   The president announced that U.S. troops would help createthe encampments in an effort to hasten humanitarianassistance to tens of thousands of Kurdish refugees. Bushsaid the Kurds would be encouraged to move to the protectedcamps from remote mountainous areas along Iraq's borders withTurkey and Iran. He stressed that the action was &quot;an interimmeasure designed to meet an immediate, penetratinghumanitarian need,&quot; and that the U.S. hadn't any intention ofintervening militarily in Iraq's internal affairs.</LP><TEXT>   U.N. Secretary-General Perez de Cuellar said he wouldinstruct international legal authorities to consider an ECproposal to try Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein for war crimes.   ---   THE SUPREME COURT MADE it tougher for death-row inmates toappeal.   The high court, by a 6-3 vote, narrowed the rights ofconvicted criminals, especially those on death row, to filerepeated challenges to the constitutionality of theirconvictions. The justices ruled that a Georgia inmate abusedthe legal process known as habeas corpus by filing a secondround of legal challenges to his 1978 murder conviction.Conservatives have complained that prisoners drag out deathsentences by filing habeas corpus petitions rehashing oldissues or raising new ones that could have been raisedearlier.   The dissenters, Marshall, Blackmun and Stevens, accusedthe court of substituting its own rules for those of Congresswith regard to defendants' rights without acknowledging thechange.   ---   Israel flouted Baker's call for Mideast&quot;confidence-building gestures,&quot; allowing Jewish settlers toestablish a community in the occupied West Bank. InWashington, the White House said the settlement at Revava was&quot;an obstacle to peace.&quot; Baker is due in Jerusalem tomorrowfor a third round of shuttle diplomacy.                                                                                                          Shamir pressed his Soviet counterpart, Pavlov, for therestoration of diplomatic ties as a necessary prelude to aregional peace conference. The Israeli and Soviet primeministers were in London for the inauguration of the EuropeanBank for Reconstruction and Development.   ---   Gorbachev and Kaifu held talks and agreed to tackle theirlongstanding dispute over four islands off Japan's northerncoast. Gorbachev, making the first visit by a Soviet leaderto Japan, is hoping to improve relations between the twocountries and gain pledges of economic assistance from theJapanese.                                                                                                          The Soviet Parliament gave initial approval to a billproposed by Gorbachev that would ban political strikes.Separately, the president of Georgia ordered the southernrepublic's government agencies to support strikes and civildisobedience as part of its campaign to secure independence.   ---   South Africa banned &quot;dangerous weapons&quot; at publicgatherings in a bid to curb black factional violence, butofficials didn't bow to demands by the opposition AfricanNational Congress for a law against traditional tribal arms.Separately, the ANC disclosed plans for paramilitaryself-defense units, a move condemned by the police.   ---   About 700,000 workers staged a strike at textile, metaland leather factories throughout Serbia, Yugoslavia's largestrepublic, in a walkout termed the biggest since the formercommunist party won free elections in December. Many of theworkers are demanding wages they haven't received for monthsbecause of an economic crisis.   ---   A report on estrogen found that women who took estrogenpills for 15 years were 30% more likely to develop breastcancer. The review of 16 earlier clinical studies shows thecancer risk is lower than some earlier studies suggested, butthe report doesn't make clear whether the risk outweighs thebenefits.   ---   Nicaragua needs more U.S. aid as it faces the &quot;almostimpossible&quot; task of building a democracy from the ruins ofcivil war and economic collapse, President Chamorro toldCongress. But House Speaker Foley said lawmakers instead arelikely to urge the White House to expedite aid dollarsalready allocated but not yet disbursed.   ---   Chilean health authorities reported a case of cholera inthat country, indicating the epidemic that already has killed1,000 people in Peru has spread to a fourth nation in SouthAmerica.   ---   Died: David Lean, 83, British director of large-scale filmepics who won Academy Awards for &quot;Bridge on the River Kwai&quot;and &quot;Lawrence of Arabia,&quot; in London.</TEXT></DOC>